        title: 'Reasoning, Argumentation and Debate',
        tips: ['Use sentence starters: "One strength was... because..."', 'Encourage pupils to connect to success criteria and each other\'s ideas.', 'Structured discussion develops metacognition and reasoning.'],
        content: '<h3>Promoting Reflection</h3><p>The EEF evidence suggests that promoting reasoning, argumentation and debate helps develop metacognition. It encourages pupils to reflect on their learning, the learning of others, and draw connections between topics.</p><h3>In Drama Critique</h3><p>After a performance, use structured discussion: "What worked? Why? What would improve it? Justify your view." Pupils must reason, not just state opinions. "I think the use of space worked because..."</p><h3>In Art and Photography</h3><p>Peer critique of work in progress: "What has this piece achieved? What evidence supports that? What would develop it further?" Encourage pupils to connect to success criteria and to each other\'s ideas.</p><h3>Structured Discussion</h3><p>Use sentence starters: "One strength was... because..." "To improve, I would... because..." "This connects to... because..." Over time, pupils internalise the language of reflection and reasoning.</p><h3>Key Takeaway</h3><p>Metacognition supports learner independence. Teach it explicitly, model it, embed it in your usual curriculum. The impact is high and the cost is low.</p>',
